# AI-DLC trigger-critical SKILL evals (Tier-2 routing records; see ../README.md).
# A `target` here is a skill whose value depends on loading at the right moment.
# Triggering prompts must NOT name the skill — CI rejects skill-name-in-query.
# Linted for QUALITY only; behavior is judged in the manual model-in-the-loop loop.

# ---- architecture-design  (vs implementation-planning) ----
{"id": "ad-pos-1", "target": "architecture-design", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Before any code, propose a couple of logical architectures for this service with their trade-offs, the domain model, and the data contracts, then let me pick.", "expectation": "Loads architecture-design: structure/contracts before code, 2+ options for the arbiter."}
{"id": "ad-near-1", "target": "architecture-design", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "The structure is decided — turn this unit into an ordered set of build steps and surface what's blocked vs parallel.", "expectation": "Must NOT load architecture-design. Correct target: implementation-planning — ordering the build, not designing it."}

# ---- implementation-planning  (vs architecture-design) ----
{"id": "ip-pos-1", "target": "implementation-planning", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Take this approved unit of work and sequence it into dependency-aware build steps; tell me what can go in parallel and produce the handoff for the build.", "expectation": "Loads implementation-planning: sequencing a unit into ordered build steps."}
{"id": "ip-near-1", "target": "implementation-planning", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "We still need to choose the module boundaries and define the interfaces between components — give me options with trade-offs.", "expectation": "Must NOT load implementation-planning. Correct target: architecture-design — structure/boundaries, not sequence."}

# ---- code-review  (vs rca-investigation) ----
{"id": "crv-pos-1", "target": "code-review", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Look over this PR before we merge — does the change satisfy the unit's real intent, are there regressions, and what's your verdict?", "expectation": "Loads code-review: pre-merge review with an enumerated verdict."}
{"id": "crv-near-1", "target": "code-review", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "This feature was working last week and now it's broken in prod — reproduce it and find the true cause before we change anything.", "expectation": "Must NOT load code-review. Correct target: rca-investigation — an observed failure, not a pre-merge gate."}

# ---- rca-investigation  (vs code-review) ----
{"id": "rca-pos-1", "target": "rca-investigation", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "A nightly job started failing intermittently after a config change. Isolate it, diagnose the real cause, and tell me who should own the fix.", "expectation": "Loads rca-investigation: reproduce/isolate/diagnose an observed failure; investigate-only."}
{"id": "rca-near-1", "target": "rca-investigation", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Here's a proposed diff. Gate it before merge — correctness and any regressions it might introduce.", "expectation": "Must NOT load rca-investigation. Correct target: code-review — nothing is broken; this is a pre-merge gate."}

# ---- requirements-elaboration ----
{"id": "re-pos-1", "target": "requirements-elaboration", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "This ask is fuzzy. Help me clarify it, write testable acceptance criteria and explicit non-goals, set the risk tier, and slice the units of work to open Construction.", "expectation": "Loads requirements-elaboration: Inception elaboration — criteria, non-goals, risk_tier, unit slicing."}
{"id": "re-near-1", "target": "requirements-elaboration", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Requirements are locked. Now define the domain model and the component boundaries with a couple of options.", "expectation": "Must NOT load requirements-elaboration. Correct target: architecture-design — structural design after requirements."}

# ---- testing-strategy ----
{"id": "ts-pos-1", "target": "testing-strategy", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Design the oracle for this unit — what levels to test at, cover every acceptance criterion, and write the assertions so passing means it's genuinely right, not gamed.", "expectation": "Loads testing-strategy: designing the oracle, levels, intent-checking, don't-edit-the-oracle rule."}
{"id": "ts-near-1", "target": "testing-strategy", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "The tests already exist and pass — now write the product code that makes them green.", "expectation": "Must NOT load testing-strategy. Correct target: the implementer's path — writing product code, not the oracle."}

# ---- security-review  (lightweight lens vs escalation to the security agent) ----
{"id": "srv-pos-1", "target": "security-review", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Quick check on this change — is it safe, could any of it be exploited? It touches input parsing and a file upload.", "expectation": "Loads security-review: standing lightweight lens; covers injection/upload, and the escalation boundary."}
{"id": "srv-near-1", "target": "security-review", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "We're designing a brand-new authentication scheme with token exchange and need a full, prioritized deep threat model of it before we build.", "expectation": "Loads security-review only as the lens that STOPS and escalates; the deep work goes to the dedicated security agent. Pass criterion: it recognizes the high-risk trigger and escalates rather than handling it as a routine lens pass."}

# ---- citation-verification ----
{"id": "cv-pos-1", "target": "citation-verification", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Before this literature review ships, confirm every reference is real, that each quote and statistic traces to its source, and flag anything you can't confirm.", "expectation": "Loads citation-verification: the blocking gate — re-fetch, confirm support, date/confidence-tag via the ledger."}
{"id": "cv-near-1", "target": "citation-verification", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Go out and gather fresh sources on this topic for one slice of the question and return cited findings.", "expectation": "Must NOT load citation-verification. Correct target: research-method/researcher — gathering sources, not verifying an existing draft's citations."}

# ---- research-method ----
{"id": "rm-pos-1", "target": "research-method", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "I want a thorough multi-source landscape review comparing options with citations — how should we fan out the searching across workers and then synthesize?", "expectation": "Loads research-method: fan-out/fan-in workflow, worker scaling, source-quality heuristics."}
{"id": "rm-near-1", "target": "research-method", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Sequence this approved unit of work into ordered, dependency-aware build steps.", "expectation": "Must NOT load research-method. Correct target: implementation-planning — build sequencing, not research."}

# ---- writing-docs  (inline self-serve vs the documentation agent for doc sets) ----
{"id": "wd-pos-1", "target": "writing-docs", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Add a short README section and a docstring for the helper I just wrote, with a runnable example.", "expectation": "Loads writing-docs inline: single co-located doc, self-served (not escalated to the documentation agent)."}
{"id": "wd-near-1", "target": "writing-docs", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "We need an entire multi-page user guide and contributor handbook with a navigation structure — plan the IA and write it all.", "expectation": "Must NOT self-serve via writing-docs. Correct target: the documentation agent — multi-file docs-as-deliverable."}

# ---- aidlc-workflow  (the loop) vs aidlc-methodology (the concepts) ----
{"id": "aw-pos-1", "target": "aidlc-workflow", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "We're starting this project's lifecycle. Walk me through running Inception then Construction, the arbiter sign-off gates, and how much ceremony a trivial change needs.", "expectation": "Loads aidlc-workflow: the step-by-step lifecycle loop, gates, triage."}
{"id": "aw-near-1", "target": "aidlc-workflow", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "I just need to understand the vocabulary — what IS a bolt, a unit of work, and what does 'the human as arbiter' actually mean?", "expectation": "Must NOT load aidlc-workflow. Correct target: aidlc-methodology — concept/definition grounding, not the procedure."}

# ---- aidlc-methodology ----
{"id": "am-pos-1", "target": "aidlc-methodology", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Explain the four values of this methodology and the difference between AI-driven, AI-managed, and AI-assisted, plus why agents stand in for a 'mob'.", "expectation": "Loads aidlc-methodology: concepts/values/definitions reference knowledge."}
{"id": "am-near-1", "target": "aidlc-methodology", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Actually run the next phase for me — take us through the Construction loop and its arbiter gate step by step.", "expectation": "Must NOT load aidlc-methodology. Correct target: aidlc-workflow — running the loop, not defining terms."}

# ---- delivery-operations ----
{"id": "do-pos-1", "target": "delivery-operations", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "We're ready to ship. Build the CI/CD pipeline and IaC, set up monitoring and a rollback plan, and run the pre-deploy checklist — who authorizes the deploy?", "expectation": "Loads delivery-operations: Operations playbook — deploy/release/IaC/monitoring/rollback under the deploy gate."}
{"id": "do-near-1", "target": "delivery-operations", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "The production service is erroring right now — find out why it broke.", "expectation": "Must NOT load delivery-operations. Correct target: rca-investigation — diagnosing an observed failure, not shipping."}

# ---- conventional-commits ----
{"id": "cc-pos-1", "target": "conventional-commits", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "How should I word this commit message for the breaking change I'm about to land, and what type/scope applies?", "expectation": "Loads conventional-commits: type/scope/description format and breaking-change markers."}
{"id": "cc-near-1", "target": "conventional-commits", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Review this diff before I merge and tell me if it's correct.", "expectation": "Must NOT load conventional-commits. Correct target: code-review — a pre-merge review, not commit-message formatting."}

# ---- extending-the-kit  (vs aidlc-workflow for product features) ----
{"id": "etk-pos-1", "target": "extending-the-kit", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Our installed agent roster has no coverage for our Go microservice stack. Add new components so future work in this repo automatically follows our Go conventions.", "expectation": "Loads extending-the-kit: authoring/adding .claude/ kit components for a new stack/conventions (propose-for-approval), not building a product feature."}
{"id": "etk-near-1", "target": "extending-the-kit", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Build the 'export to CSV' feature for our app — run it through requirements, design, and implementation.", "expectation": "Must NOT load extending-the-kit. Correct target: aidlc-workflow — running the lifecycle to build a product feature, not extending the kit."}

# ---- observability-practice  (vs delivery-operations) ----
{"id": "obp-pos-1", "target": "observability-practice", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Decide what we should measure for the checkout service — the SLIs, the service-level objectives, and an error budget — and how to instrument it so a slow request is traceable.", "expectation": "Loads observability-practice: designing WHAT to measure — SLIs/SLOs/error budgets/instrumentation."}
{"id": "obp-near-1", "target": "observability-practice", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Stand up the release pipeline and deploy this build, with a rollback if the smoke checks fail.", "expectation": "Must NOT load observability-practice. Correct target: delivery-operations — deploy/release/rollback mechanics, not measurement design."}

# ---- dependency-compliance  (vs security-review) ----
{"id": "dc-pos-1", "target": "dependency-compliance", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "We're about to vendor a GPL-licensed library into our MIT product. Check whether the licenses are compatible and whether we can legally ship it, and produce a software bill of materials.", "expectation": "Loads dependency-compliance: license compatibility / SBOM / what you may legally ship — the supply-chain compliance lens."}
{"id": "dc-near-1", "target": "dependency-compliance", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Is this third-party package vulnerable — could a known CVE in it be exploited against us?", "expectation": "Must NOT load dependency-compliance. Correct target: security-review — exploitability of a dependency, not its licensing/compliance."}

# ---- ux-design  (vs architecture-design) ----
{"id": "ux-pos-1", "target": "ux-design", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Design the screen flow and the interaction for our new onboarding wizard, and make sure it's accessible to keyboard and screen-reader users.", "expectation": "Loads ux-design: interface/interaction/screen-flow and accessibility for UI-bearing work."}
{"id": "ux-near-1", "target": "ux-design", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Decide the system's components, module boundaries, and the contracts between them before we build.", "expectation": "Must NOT load ux-design. Correct target: architecture-design — system structure/boundaries/contracts, not interface design."}

# ---- design-system  (the visual-design lens; vs ux-design and architecture-design) ----
{"id": "ds-pos-1", "target": "design-system", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Our app's screens look inconsistent and unstyled. Define our design tokens — colors, spacing, typography — and an inventory of every UI element with all of its visual states (default, hover, active, focus, disabled, loading, selected, error) so we have one committed look to build against.", "expectation": "Loads design-system: design tokens, UI element inventory with full state matrices, a committed aesthetic — the testable visual contract."}
{"id": "ds-pos-2", "target": "design-system", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Pin down the visual language for the dashboard: the token palette, and a consistent global treatment for empty, loading, and error states across every card and table.", "expectation": "Loads design-system: tokens plus the global empty/loading/error visual patterns and state coverage — the aesthetic contract, not flows or structure."}
{"id": "ds-near-1", "target": "design-system", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Design the navigation and screen flow for our checkout, lay out the information architecture, and make sure it's usable and meets WCAG keyboard and contrast requirements.", "expectation": "Must NOT load design-system. Correct target: ux-design — IA, interaction/flow, usability and WCAG accessibility behavior, not the visual token/state contract."}
{"id": "ds-near-2", "target": "design-system", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Before we build, decide this system's component boundaries, the module structure, and which framework and persistence approach to use, with a couple of options and trade-offs.", "expectation": "Must NOT load design-system. Correct target: architecture-design — system structure, component/module boundaries, and tech choices; the word 'component' here means a code module, not a styled UI element."}

# ---- spec-conformance  (the completeness/no-deferral checklist at Gate 3; vs code-review, requirements-elaboration, testing-strategy) ----
{"id": "sc-pos-1", "target": "spec-conformance", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Is this unit actually done end-to-end, or did we quietly defer or orphan something? Check that every acceptance criterion is met, that nothing is a feature wired to nothing, and that the docs, tests, and changelog came with it.", "expectation": "Loads spec-conformance: the enumerated completeness checklist — requirement coverage, end-to-end reachability (no orphans), companion freshness, and a delivered-vs-spec converge/anti-deferral diff with 'show, don't assert' evidence."}
{"id": "sc-pos-2", "target": "spec-conformance", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Walk the delivered change against what the unit promised in its acceptance criteria and non-goals — enumerate each item, show me concrete evidence it's satisfied rather than just asserting it, and call out anything we silently pushed to a 'later phase'.", "expectation": "Loads spec-conformance: delivered-vs-spec diff over native acceptance_criteria/non_goals, anti-deferral converge check, evidence-not-assertion per item."}
{"id": "sc-near-1", "target": "spec-conformance", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Review this PR diff before we merge — is the change correct, does it introduce any regressions, and what's your verdict?", "expectation": "Must NOT load spec-conformance. Correct target: code-review — pre-merge correctness/regression review with an enumerated verdict, not the completeness/no-deferral checklist."}
{"id": "sc-near-2", "target": "spec-conformance", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "We're scoping a new feature. Write the user stories and the testable acceptance criteria for it, with explicit non-goals.", "expectation": "Must NOT load spec-conformance. Correct target: requirements-elaboration — authoring the acceptance criteria/stories up front, not auditing a delivered unit against them."}
{"id": "sc-near-3", "target": "spec-conformance", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Design the test oracle for this unit — decide what levels to test at and which tests to write so passing genuinely proves the intent.", "expectation": "Must NOT load spec-conformance. Correct target: testing-strategy — designing the test oracle/coverage, not the completeness audit of a finished unit."}

# ---- stack-binding  (detect/bind the repo stack + set up visual QA; vs design-system and architecture-design) ----
{"id": "sb-pos-1", "target": "stack-binding", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Figure out what framework and UI library this repo actually uses by reading its lockfiles and manifests, then write the config the visual checks read — which browser, run/build commands, and entry point the screenshot tooling should target.", "expectation": "Loads stack-binding: auto-detect the repo's stack from lockfiles/manifests, write .ai-dlc/stack-binding.json, and set up the repo's visual-QA so the visual checks know what to target."}
{"id": "sb-pos-2", "target": "stack-binding", "kind": "positive", "prompt": "Before the visual checks can run, we need to detect this project's framework and tokens from its package manifests and produce the JSON the screenshot/visual tooling reads — the browser, the dev-server command, and where the app boots.", "expectation": "Loads stack-binding: detect the stack from manifests and emit the visual-QA target config (the binding the deterministic visual checks consume) — not designing tokens, not choosing architecture."}
{"id": "sb-near-1", "target": "stack-binding", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Define our design tokens — colors, spacing, typography — and the component state matrix (default, hover, focus, disabled, loading, error) so we have one committed look to build against.", "expectation": "Must NOT load stack-binding. Correct target: design-system — authoring the visual token/state contract, not detecting the repo's stack or writing the visual-QA target config."}
{"id": "sb-near-2", "target": "stack-binding", "kind": "near-miss-negative", "prompt": "Before we build, choose the system structure and the module boundaries, and decide which database and framework we should use, with a couple of options and trade-offs.", "expectation": "Must NOT load stack-binding. Correct target: architecture-design — choosing structure/boundaries and tech, not auto-detecting an existing stack from lockfiles to configure visual QA."}
